===Funeral rites===
[[Image:Burial_Site_2.jpg|thumb|right|A stone carved burial site. ''Tau tau'' (effigies of the deceased) were put in the cave, facing down the land.]]
In the Toraja society, [[Funeral|funeral ritual]] is the most elaborate and expensive event.  The richer and more powerful an individual, the more expensive his or her funeral.  In the ''aluk'' religion, only nobles have the right to have an extensive death feast.<ref>In the present-day, where tourism is the main income of the Torajans, funeral feasts were held by non-noble rich families, mainly performed for tourist attractions. Volkman (1982) called this phenomenon as a death funeral inflation.</ref>

The expensive cost of death feast is often made the ceremony held in weeks, months or years after the actual death, because the deceased family needs to raise significant funds to cover the funeral expenses.<ref>In 1992, the most powerful Torajan, the former chief of Tana Toraja Regency, died and his family had asked US$ 125,000 to a Japanese TV company for a license fee to film the funeral, in order to cover the funeral expenses; cf. Yamashita (1994).</ref>  Traditionally, Torajans believe that death is not a sudden abrupt event, but rather a gradual process toward ''Puya'' (the land of souls) or the [[afterlife]].  During the waiting period, the body of the [[the dead|deceased]] is wrapped in several layers of cloth and kept under the house or tongkonan.  The soul of the deceased is thought to linger around the village until the funeral ceremony is completed, after which it begins its journey to ''Puya''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=To the Afterworld and Back: Mourning and Dreams of the Dead among the Toraja|journal=Ethos|author=Douglas Hollan|url=http://links.jstor.org/sici?sici=0091-2131%28199512%2923%3A4%3C424%3ATTAABM%3E2.0.CO%3B2-E|volume=23|issue=4|pages=424&ndash;436|date=1995}}</ref>

The death feast of a nobleman is usually attended by thousands of people and lasts for several days.  The most noticeable component in the ritual is [[water buffalo|buffalos]].  The more powerful the person who died, the more buffalos are slaughtered at their death feast.  Buffalo carcasses, including their heads, are usually lined on a field, waiting for their owner who is in the "sleeping stage". Torajans believe that the deceased person will need the buffalos to make the journey.

There are three methods of [[burial]]. The [[coffin]], including any possessions which will be needed in the afterlife, will be either put in a [[cave]] [[Grave (burial)|grave]], a stone grave, or hung on a [[cliff]].  The wealthy are often buried in a stone grave, carved out of the rocky cliff, which usually costs a lot of money and takes some months to complete.  In some places, the stone cave is enough to accommodate the whole family.  A wooden carved [[effigy]], called ''tau tau'', is usually put in the cave and faced down over the land.<ref>Unfortunately, these ''tau tau'' have been targeted by [[grave robbing|grave robbers]] for antique collectors.  In several occasions, a stolen tau tau effigy of Toraja appeared in an exhibition show, for instances, at the [[Brooklyn Museum]] in 1981 and at the Arnold Herstand Gallery in [[New York]] in 1984, see Volkman (1990).</ref>

A unique type of burial is to hang the coffin by ropes, either on a cliff face or from trees for dead babies and children  This hanging grave usually lasts for some years, until the ropes rot and the coffin falls to the ground below.

==Language==
The ethnic Toraja language is dominant in Tana Toraja, although the national [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] language is spoken in the community.<ref name="official"/>  All [[elementary school]]s in Tana Toraja teach Toraja language. [[Denominationalism|Denominations of the language]] include ''Kalumpang'', ''Mamasa'', ''Tae' '', ''Talondo' '', ''Toala' '', and ''Toraja-Sa'dan''. All of them belong to the [[Malayo-Polynesian]] language from the [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] family.<ref name="gordon2005Toraja">{{cite book|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/web.asp|last=Gordon|first=Raymond G.|title=Ethnologue: Languages of the World|date=2005|publisher=Dallas, Tex.: SIL International|format=online version|accessdate=2006-10-17}}</ref> Each denomination has its own [[dialect]]s, as seen in the table below.

